Now you are working with branches in Git. I’ll explain in very simple beginner language.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
Your remote repo is on GitHub.

🌿 What is a Branch?

Branch means:

A separate line of work.

Think like:

master → Main project

rahul1 → Your new experiment or feature
____________________________________________________________________________________________
Step-by-Step Explanation
1️⃣ git branch rahul1

👉 This creates a new branch named rahul1.

But ⚠ it does NOT switch to it yet.

You are still on master.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
2️⃣ git checkout rahul1

👉 This switches you to the branch rahul1.

Now whatever changes you make will go inside rahul1 branch, not master.

You can check branch using:

git branch

The * shows your current branch.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
3️⃣ git add .

👉 Add all changed files to staging area.

Means:

"Prepare files to save."
____________________________________________________________________________________________
4️⃣ git status

👉 Shows:

Which files changed

Which files are ready to commit

Just for checking.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
5️⃣ git commit -m "rahul1"

👉 Saves your changes inside branch rahul1.

Now your branch has its own commit.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
6️⃣ git push --set-upstream origin rahul1

This is important 👇

👉 Upload branch rahul1 to GitHub.

--set-upstream means:

Connect local branch rahul1 with remote branch rahul1.

So next time you can just type:

git push

No need to write full command again.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
🧠 Simple Real Example

Think like this:

master = Final project notebook

rahul1 = Rough work notebook

You worked in rough notebook (rahul1)
Then uploaded it to GitHub.
____________________________________________________________________________________________
🔥 Final Result

Now on GitHub you have:

master branch

rahul1 branch

Both separate.